{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_endive_ver02/data/sn86063811/00279558388/1937111601/0264.xml":{"full_text":"JILL\ntr-r*\"\nBY\n/AARY RAYMOND\nCopyr^M, H)37, NEA S\u00abrrK\u00bb, tnt\nCAST OF CHARACTERS\nJILL WENTWORTH. heroin.\n\u00abttr*clin debu tante.\nNALAN JEFFRY, hero. riin\nyoung artist.\nBARRY WENTWORTH. Jill*\nstepbrother.\nJACK WENTWORTH. Jill'\nbrother,\nSYLVIA SUTTON, oil heiren\n\nYesterday: Jill U picked up b\npolice the drove aimle\u00bb\u00bbl\nbout \u00bbhe city. The net is f**\nclosing in about her. But wha\nabout Barry. Jill recollect*? Nc\nit couldn't have been him, ih<\nrenoni What muit she do?\nCHAPTER XXIV\nAlan's apartment was Kicked\nShade* were draw n. A prvlongei\npounding by Patty, after continu\nous ringing of tht* bell. broutrh\nno response.\nShe went to the apartment nex\ndoor and pressvd the boll. Ar\nelderly man answered th\u00ab' door\nNo. he didn't know the occupant\non the other .Hide. He had oftei\nplanned to call on a fellow artist\nAnd, now. th\u00ab* young man wa:\nifone. He had seen him leaving\nthis afternoon in a cab. He hac\ncarried several large suitcase;\n*ith him.\nPatty turned away in panic\nAlan had gone away from thi\nplaco. It would be like looking\nfor a needle m a haystack, sure\nenough, trying to find an un\nknown young man in a large city.\n\"Thank 'heaven foi Ardath!'\nPatty thought, wildly. Adding\nmentally: \"And don't you dare\ngive me any trouble, Ardath, 01\nI'll tear you apart with my hands.\nYou've already caused too much\ntrouble. It's you who should be\ninvestigated. Hut women like you\nxet by with anything.\"\nHaving indulged herself by this\n\u2022nental berating <\u00bbf the despised\nArdath. Patty swung into Madi\nson avenue and headed for the\nexclusive shop where Ardath mod\neled.\n\"Wha* do you want?\" Ardath\nbegan belligerently. \"I'm pretty\nbusy it\" you don't mind\n\"I do mind.\" Patty answered.\n\"Take me to some private place\nwhere we can talk.\"\n\"What if I don't care to talk\nwith you?\"\n\"Maybe you'd rather talk with\nthe police.'*\nArdath shrugged. Hu\u00bb she led\nthe way to a small fitting room\nand closed the door.\nPatty wont directly to the\npoint. \"Anlath, Jill is in trouble.\nThe |)n!i('f think she hud some\nthing to do with the death of her\nfather, who died, they say, at\no'clock. Jill ua.-n't at home then.\nShe had just leit you at tin* door\nof Alan's apartment.\"\n\"So. she* told you that?\" Ardath\nwas smiling qucerly \"1 guess\nshe's pretty scared. Women who\nare scared will say most any\nthing.\"\n\"Tell the truth,\" Patty spoke,\nshortly.\nWhy didn't you go to Alan\nJeffry?\" Aidath asked.\n\"I did. He wasn't at home.\nThe people next door saw him\nleave this afternoon with his suit\ncase h.''\nPatty immediately regretted the\nwonts. She had seen a look in\nArdath's eyes that she recognized.\nThe lo\u00ab\u00bbk of the mt slipping be\ntween the cat's paws and into its\nown dark hole.\n\"Pretty dumb of me,\" Patty\ngroaned to hejself.\n\"Gone away, has he?\" Ardath\nmused. \"Well, even if he were\nhere. and even if 1 were at his\nplace\u2014which, remember. I'm not\nadmitting -it wouldn't help you\nany. Jill Wentworth is not,telling\nthe truth. I did n'* see her that\nmorning around 6 o'clock. You\ncan tell her for me that she'll\nhave to think up another alibi.\"\n\"Why you\u2014you terrible, un\nconscionable liar\u2014 you.\"\n\"Haul out all the compliments\nyou happen to have with you,\"\nArdath replied calmly. \"\"I guess\nI can take them. I always knew\nyou didn't like me, Patty.\"\n\"I don't like you.\" Patty spoke\nbluntly. \"But my feelings toward\nyou haven't anything to do with\nthis. You Were at Alan's because\nJill said you were. And I'll find\nAlan, and he'll say so. If you\nthink he'd shield you when Jill's\nin danger, you are not as smart\nas I think you are. You should\nknow better than anyone that he\nloves Jill.\"\nArdath did know better than\nanyone. Hate was unveiled in\nher eyes.\n\"I suppose you think all this\nsweet conversation is helping\nyour friend. Well, it isn't. She\ncan look to her smart lawyers.\nAnd if they put me on the stand,\nI'll swear she is crazy. As for\nAlan, don't you think if he were\ngoing to do anything for her,\nhe'd have called her before this?\"\nPatty drew a deep breath, and\nbegan putting on her gloves.\n\"There are ways to make peo\nple talk,\" she said slowfy. \"And\nperjury is a punishable crime.\nDon't forget that when you're\nsummoned.\"\n\"Nobody can prove I was there,\nbecause I wasn't,'' Ardath per\nsisted. \"And if Alan says so, I'll\nsay he is no gentleman 'and is\nonly trying to save Jill from pri\nson. I guess with all her looks\nand money, she'll get by with a\nfew years in prison. When she\ncomes out. she won't be so high\nhat. 1 imagine.\"\n\nt There was no help here. Tatty\nadmitted to herself that Ardath\nha\u00bbJ the upper hand. There were\ntimes when Ardath could look so\nsweet and appealing- She could\npicture Ardath with that innocent\nu look \u00bbh\u00ab had at times. looking ujj\nat a jury through a mist of ttars.\n^wearing she was being made a\nj victim to save Jill.\n1 \"1 don't believe you would tell\n1 the truth even to save Jill's life,\"\nPatty tried out suddenly.\n\"1 et's hope it won't come to\nthat.\" Ardath smiied, carefully\nusing her compact. \"After all.\nPatty, you couldn't expect me to\nI tell the world 1 was at Alan's\njust to cleai Jill Wentworth s\nskirts. What kind of girl do you\nthink I am. anyway?\"\n\"I don't have to puzzle about\ni it. 1 know.\" Patty replied grimly.\nThere was nothing- else to do.\nNo one else who could help. In\na flash it came to her. There was\nthe old woman with the red scarf\nJill had given her.\nShe must find her. Her testi\nmony and the scarf would clear\nJill.\nHut nobody on l\u00bb7th street had\nseen an old beggar woman wear\ning a red scarf.\n\"Beggars don't come on this\nstreet.\" one irate woman told\nI'atty. \"Some of us may be poor,\nbut we're all respectable, ami\nable to take care of ourselves.\nWho ever heard of such a story?\nAn old lady, begging at that time\nj of morning.\"\nI'atty turned away. Well, of\ni course Jill hadn't said the old\nlady was a beggar. Hut she had\nkept the money Jill had given\ni her. which amounted to the same\nthing. And these cold mornings,\nshe would be sure to wear that\nred woolen scarf. She has cover\ned every place in the block. No.\nthere was the apartment next\ndoor to Alan's, occupied by an\nelderly artist. She would go back\nto him, and toll her story once\nmore. If he couldn't help, she\nwould ask the police to keep a\nlookout for an old woman wear\ning a red scarf. Iteyond that\u2014but\nPatty wouldn't think beyond that.\n\nOne** more, fatty rang the* boll\nof the apartment that adjoined\nAlan's.\nAnd again the friendly face of\nth\u00ab- elderly man appeared.\n\"Still looking for the young\nman?\" he queried, fx'lore Patty\ncould speak. \"I'm afraid I've no\nnews. I havent seen him since\nhe left today. And nobo<|y has\ncome to his apartment.\"\n\"No.\" Patty answered. \"I'm not\nlooking for him now. I'm trying\nto find an \u00ab\u00bbld woman\u2014\"\n\"An old woman!\" The elderly\nman Mailed. \"So it's an old wo\nman instead of a young man you\nwant to find?\"\nPatty smiled wanly hack at him. j\ncourse, she did sound crazy.\nHut somehow she must convince\nhim she was not.\n\"Someone a girl friend of\nmine is in great trouble,\" Patty\nsaid. \"This young man and an\nold woman who was begging in\nfront the day my friend came\nhere are the only two people who\ncould help her.\"\n\"We have no beggars,\" the man\nb\u00ab:iran stiffly.\n\"I've heard that before,\" Patty\nanswered. \"Just the same there\nwas an old woman in front of this|\ni building, and nr\u00bby friend gave her\nsome money and a red woolen\nscarf\u2014\"\n\"A red scarf!\" the man ex\nclaimed. \"Oh, of course. Will you\ncome in?\"\nPatty walked in. She had a\nnervous feeling that maybe she\nshouldn't be following him. His\n1 eyes had gleamed so queer ly at\nj th* mention of the red scarf.\nThey were walking down a hall.\nAnd now the man was throwing\nj a door wide.\n\nSeated near a glowing fire,\nknitting briskly, was an ancient\nlooking old woman. About her\nshoulders was a cheery red scarf.\n\"Nanna,\" began the man stern\n\"did you take some money\ni !r<\u00bbm a young woman when you\nwent out tor a breath of air early\nyesterday morning? And where\ndid you get that scarf\"\nThe old woman's bright eyes\nI twinkled. \"Did she repent her\nbargain and want the pretty scarf\nback? Or maybe she didn't know\nit was a beeg bill she was giving\ni me\nThe man shook his head in\nmock disapproval. \"You'd never\nknow that you were the mother\nof a respectable painter. Shame\nless. Taking money. No wonder\nthis young lady was out search\ning for a beggar.\"\nHe turned to Patty: \"She gets\nup every morning at (I and goes\nout for a brief while. She had\nthe habit back in France, and I\nhaven t been able to break her of\nit, though the winter mornings\nhere and in the south of France\nart- v\u00ab*ry <Hfl*erent.\"\nShe looked at her watch and\nsaid. 'It's seex o'clock',\" the old\nwoman broke in merrily. \"And I\n>aid. You don't have to tell me\nthe time. I know by the sun.' So\npretty she was. So ashamed she\nwould have been, if I geeve the\nmoney back.\"\nPatty sat down weakly- \"Please\n1 excuse me. But I feel a little\n1 Oc TAXI\nPHONES 4 and 54\n10c Per Passenger in City\ni\nBEAUTIFYING\nOF ROADSIDES\nIS SUGGESTED\nProf. Randolph Has Sim\nple Plan to Make County\nMore Attractive\nBy PROF A G. RANDOLPH\nWe who air privileged to live\nhere in wonderful W estern North\nCarolina arv surrounded by many\nof the most entrancing scenic\ngrandeurs of nature, much fertile\nland for growing foo<l and cattle,\nhills and valleys that before the\nruthless intrusions of grasping\nmen were covered with virgin for\nests of finest timber, which still\nare struggling t\u00ab> maintain this\nnatural growth wherever possible,\nand a climate whose health giving\ncharacteristics are the envy of all\nAmerica.\nSurrounded as we are by these\nabundant natural blessings, it is\nour high privilege and our solemn\nduty not only to maintain these\nwonderful gilts of nature in the\nperfection in which they were en*\ntrusted to our cure for our pleas\nure and for our benefit, but also\nto use our God-given faculties for\nimproving them and making them\nmore valuable to ourselves and to\nothers.\nHave we kept faith in fulfilling\nour duties and the obligations de\nvolving upon us as citizens <>f this\nhighly favored land? Any human\nbeing with average normal intel\nligence can, by even the most\ncasual ulance around him, see\nmany evidences of ignorance, in\ndifference, carelessness, deter\nioration, and in many cases, of\nwilful devastation and wanton\nwaste.\nLooking at this question purely\nfrom the standpoint of making a\nliving, and also from that of mak\ning a reasonable profit from our\nefforts, almost anyone experienc\ned in the economic feature of the\nlife of the average person in this\nsection must realize without ques\ntion the value of the tourist activ\nities in this section. The tourist\nbusiness is almost universally\nrecognized as one of the most\nvaluable economic assets of the\npeople living here permanently.\nWhatever can help make this sec\ntion more attractive to our tour\nists is worth careful consideration\nfaint. After I recover a bit, 1\nwant you and your son to go with\nme to the police. The girl who\ngave you the red seaif is in trou\nble. The police claim she was\nsomewhere else at yesterday\nmorning.\"\n\"They do, do they?\" began the\nold woman. \"Those police! Well,\nI guess this will prove something.\nAre those the girl's what do you\nsay in your Kngleesh\u2014ineetials?\"\nShe took the red scarf from her\nshoulders and handed it to Patty.\nInside were the letters, embroid\nered on a silk marking band,\n\"J.W.\"\n(To be concluded)\nand study.\nThe writ or native of one of\nthe host sections of one of the\nmost progressive counties of\nPiedmont North Carolina, but has\nalways liked ami valued tin* at\ntractions of the mountain section\nof the state, where he has lived\nfor a number of years, admiring\nits beauties and advantages, and\noften deploring certain shortcom\nings and deteriorating factors. He\nwishes to suggest at least one I\nidea in which every citizen can\ntake some part toward making\nour county more attractive for\nour tourists and for our own peo\nple.\nMuch can he done toward mak-;\ning our county attractive by em\nploying simple methods of beauti\nfying our roadsides ami our home\nsurroundings. We have miles and\nmiles of eroded and badly scarred\nloadsides an eyesore both to our\nown titir.ons end also to our tour\nists\u2014that can be very easily rem\nedied and made attractive by a\nlittle thought and a little work\ndone at odd times, when the land\nowners or the people of tho com\nmunity are idle or can easily\nspare the time and do a small\namount of work needed in plant\ning trees along the roadside or in\nplanting honeysuckle vines at the\ntop of unsightly hanks along the\nroadside.\nRunning a furrow, placing in it\nsome honeysuckle loots or vines,\nand covering them will be all that i\nis needed in the way of work to j\nstop erosion and scarring of the'\nbank and to start the covering of\nmany an unsightly roadside clay\nbank with an attractive vine.\nThis will also often save erosion\nof the land back of it and pre\nvent the loss of valuable soil. A\nblanket or rambling roses of vari\nous colors is also often used to\ngreat advantage in beautifying\nroadsides, especially in the vicin\nity of homes along the road.\nThe planting of some well-se\nlected trees along the roadside,\nsuch as white pines, maples, white\noaks, post oaks, or other good\ntypes, or perhaps some good fruit\ntrees in certain locations, will of\nton take away the unsightly, bar\nion appearance of the land ad\ni jacont to the road or around some\nI dwelling house, and will make it\nattractive to the passer-by.\nIn many places grass can be\nused to good advantage, and this\nis also one of the best means of\npreventing or overcoming erosion,\nthe great thief of plant food so\nmuch needed in our fields, pas\nture lands and woodlands.\nSome careful thinking, a rea\nsonable amount of intelligent\nl work, based on wholesome inter\nest, such care as ought naturally\nto be given, and patient waiting\nover a comparatively short period\nof time, will result in an improve\nment in the attractiveness and\nvalue of our county that will bo\na real eye-opener to our tourists\nwho may return for a visit here\nafter being away for a few years,\nami will in the meantime make\nour own home section much more\npleasant and worth while to our\nown home-loving citizens. Lot's\nI get together and do what we\nI ought to do along this lino.\n1'razil is sending twice as much\nI cotton to other countries as a\nyear ago.\nKHESNN IN\nTRADE IS NOT\nYET SERIOUS\nPresident States View in\nMessage But Asks for\nQuick Action\nWASHINGTON, Nov. 1*5. (I'P)\npresident Roosevelt warned con\ntrr\u00ab *ss yesterday thai there has\nbeen a \"marked\" industrial reces\nsion and proposed that it be corn\nbatted by quick action on his lcg\nislative program and by revising\ntax laws particularly to aid small\nbusiness men but also to remove\ninequalities to all.\nHe said in a message to the leg\nislators as they assembled in spe\ncial session that the business de\ncline has not reached \"serious pro\npoitions\" and cautioned that with\nthe exercise of \"ordinary pru\ndence\" there is no reason why\n\"we should suffer any prolonged\nrecession, let alone any general\neconomic paralysis.''\nbut. the chief executive empha\nsized. the slump has had the ef\nfect of decreasing the national in\ncome\u2014\"and thai is u matter of\nilefimte concern.\" The immediate\ntask is to try to increase employ\nment by the use of private cap\nital. he said, adding:\n\"Obviously government cannot\nlet nature take its course without\nregard to consequence*. If private\nenterprise does not j;\\spond. gov\neminent must take up the slack.\"\nHe appealed to congress and the\nnation as a whole to co-operate.\nMr. Roosevelt outlined in detail\nthe following four-point legisla\ntive program on which he said he\nhoped for early action \"lor the\nsake of the nation\":\n1. An \"all weather\" agricultural\ncrop control bill.\nli. Wages and hours legislation.\n3. Creation of \"seven TYA\" dis\ntricts for tin- conservation and\ndevelopment of the i.ation's nat\nural resources.\n\u2022t. Government reorganization.\nAlthough the president's mes\nsage was conciliatory and devoid\nof usual criticism of business, he\nmade it plain that there would be\nno retreat from the \"wide social\nprogiam\" initiated under the new\nileal. Its objectives were given in\nIhe message as:\n1. Higher standards of living.\n2. Wider distribution of an \"im\nmensely enlarged\" national in\ncome.\nThe message clearly reflected\nthe administration's concern over\nthe trade slump but sought to\ntjuiet fears over the scope of the\nrecession as well as stop a run\naway tax reform campaign that\nlias gained momentum with each\nNew business decline. The assem\nbling legislators appeared deter\nmined to make sharp revisions in\nthe revenue laws with or without\nthe administration's consent.\nPresident Roosevelt said he hail\nsought the advice of managers of\nlaige industrial and financial en\nterprises. of owners o! small busi\nnesses and of representatives of\nIUKl \u00bbL UIl UI 1' <11111 U1 1UIMII MllVl* llll\nbusiness outlook became acute,\ni Those discussions, h\" said, make\nI it clear that \"we have enough wis\ndom in the country today not only\nto check the present recession lc.it\nto lay the ground work foi a more\npermanent recovery.\"\nMr. Roosevelt prop* sod that the\nI \"all weather\" farm program which\nhe seeks from congress should he\ndirected at obtaining \"abundance\nwithout waste\" and have soil con\nservation as its principal goal. In\nmoving toward such a goal, the\npresident asked the legislators to\nkeep in mind: the fertility of the\nsoil; economic welfare of farm\nfamilies; fair treatment to the\nconsumers; the \"American Demo\ncratic way\" of majority iuIo and\ni the United States treasury.\nSuch a program, he said, should\nbe \"planned and administered, so\nfar as possible,\" by the farmers\nbut authority should be supplied\nto prevent an uncooperative mi\nnority from \"destroying the pro\ni coeds of the toil of the great ma\n1 jotity.\" He warned emphatically\nthat if the new farm act provides\nfor expenditures beyond budget\nappropriations that \"additional\nmeans\" must he provided to sup\nply the needed revenue,\nj Mr. Roosevelt said the country\nrecognizes the need of congres\nsional action to maintain wage in\ncome and purchasing power. Uuv\ning power, he contended, is seri\nously affected by; (1) the exploi\ntation of child labor; (2) the un\ndercutting of wages and (:i) the\nstretching of the hours of the\npoorest paid workers. Such adjust\nments, the president insisted,\nshould not be made at the \"ex\npense of those least able to bear\nthem.\"\nI Uniform minimum hour and\nwage standards are the ultimate\ngoal of the prospective labor\nmeasure but, the president said,\nthis is not an immediate necessity.\n\"We should provide flexib'e\nmachinery which will enable in\nj dustries throughout the country\n1 to adjust themselves progressively\nI to better labor conditions,\" h's\nI message said. \"Rut we must not\nforget that no policy of flexibility\nwill be practical unless a co-ordi\nnating agency has the obligation\nof inspection and investigation to\nensure the recognition and en\nforcement of what the law re\nquires.\"\nMr. Roosevelt said that it is\n\"high time\" that there be enacted\nlegislation relating to goods mov\ning in or competing with inter\nstate commerce which would:\n1. Hanist\\. child labor and pro\ntect workers unable to protect\nthemselves from excessively low\nwages and excessively long hours.\nli. End the \"unsound practice\"\nof some communities which seek\nnew industries by offering as the\nprincipal attraction labor more\nplentiful and much cheaper than\nmay be found in competing com\nmunities.\nThe message defended his pro\nposed government reorganization\nprogram as necessary to increase\nefficiency, minimize error, dupli\ncation and waste and raise the\nmorale of the public service. Of\nequal importance. Mr. Roosevelt\nsaid, is \"intelligent reorganization\nof our methods of spending na\ntional funds for the conservation\nand development of those natural\nresources which are the founda\n:on of a virile national life.\nrAiLA tmciuitnti\nCHAIRMAN FOR THE\nCOUNTY'S RED CROSS\nNathan Put la hi .s been named\nHenderson county emergency lv\u00ab-<i\nCross chairman, J. Coston,\nchairman of the organization in\nHenderson county, announced to\nday.\nIn this capacity Mr. Pat la will\nserve as chairman in any emer\ngency call by the national organ\nization, such as th\u00ab- flood last\nyear.\nMr. Patla holds a similar posi\ntion with the Hubert M. Smith\npost of the American Legion and\nhis Red Cross appointment will\nco-ordinate these 'wo agencies in\nany emergency, Mr. Cotton point\ned out.\nMr. Patla served as chairman\nof the relief campaign for flood\nsufferers last year ami his work\nwas outstanding.\nWEAR DOG COLLARS\nCOLl'MHIA, Mo. (CP i.\u2014Co\neds at the University of Missouri\nare going to the dog*\u2014at least,\nas far as their clothes are con\ncerned. Three girls the other day\nappeared on the campus wearing\ndog collurs complete with brass\nstuds, name plates and locks.\nItaly has the greatest number\nof employed since I !\u00bb38.\n'\u2022MMMMMlHHnHHl\nMONDAY\n.Maximum\u2014.*>k decree*. Mini\nmum- Hi decree.-. \u20141<;\nu]\u00bb\u2022\u00bb\u2022>. I>ayV range- 2j degrees.\nNormal mean temperature for\nNovi mber\u2014{\u00bb!. J \u00abRain\nlull to date\u2014.7- inches. Normal\nrainfall for November\u20143.11 in\nches.\nCARD OF THANKS\nWe express our appreciation of\nthe great kinfine^ and sympathy\nof our friend# in cur bereave\nment; for floral tributes ami\nevery word of comfoi* and friend\nship.\nMrs. Denton Orr and Family.\nIt's Easy To Bs Mistaken About\nSTOMACH TROUBLE\nStomach sufferers should learn ths\ntruth about ULCERS, GIS, ACID,\nINDIGESTION, belching, heartburn,\nconstipation, etc., due to excess acid.\nFREE UDGA Booklet contains facta\nof interest. The9th edition, justoffthe\npress, may prove your tirst step to hap*\npy stomach comfort! (,'liji this to remind\nyou to ask for the UDGA Booklet at\nECONOMY DRUGS\nMain St. and Fifth Ave.\nPure, Clean Coal\nA COAL FOR EVERY PURPOSE\nKay-Jay Coal for (he Furnace\nRed Clover and Blue Gem Coal\nExcellent for All Purposes\nCreech Coal\nAll zes and all-purpose coal, including oil-treated,\ndustless stoker nut coal\nPAY CASH-SAVE MONEY\nCoal is advancing but we stocked up to protect our\ncustomers and you may have it at the old price for\ncash, if you buy now.\nBUY NOW AND SAVE MONEY ON ANY\nQUANTITY FROM A CARLOAD TO A\nWHEELBARROW FULL\nBurning tests prove the superiority of our coal. Tell\nus your needs and we will deliver the coal that will\ngive you the most satisfaction.\nPHONE 175 AT THE DEPOT\nZ>0 G01F\u00a3RS /1PPRBCM7E\n^awiascomm tobaccos?\n\nIT means a lot that famous golfers like Gene Sarazen, Helen\nHicks, Lawson Little, and Ralph Guldahl, agree in their preference\nfor Camels. They have found that costlier tobaccos do place Camels\nin a class apart. Listen to Ralph Guldahl, National Open Champion:\n\"I've stuck to Camels for 10 years,\" he says. \"I smoke lots of\nCamels and I've never known them to jangle my nerves. That\npartly explains why so many golfers are loyal Camel smokers.\"\nAnd not only golfers, but people in all walks of life\u2014millions of\nAmericans\u2014prefer Camels day after day after day, making them the\nLARGEST-SELLING cigarette in America...or the world.\nSALESGIRL Elsie Schu\ninacher: \"When the rush\nRets me 'worn out'-it's me\nfor a Camel, and I get a\nquick 'lift.' Practically all\nof us girls in the store pre\nfer Camels.\"\nWATCHMAKER I. C.\nGorkun says: \"Camels?\nSay, every Camel I smoke\nseems to be milder and\ntastier than the last one.\nCumels don't leuve me\nfeeling '*muked out.'\"\nSPORTS WRITER\nStunrt Cameron: \"It's\nmighty impressive how\nchampions agree on\nCamels. I'm glad as nny\nathlete that Camels don't\nget on my nerves.\"\nDRAFTSMAN B. T.\nMiller:\"! often feel used\nup during long hours be\nfore the drawing board.\nCamels give me a 'lift'\nwhen I feel I need it. They\n(sever life aiy taste.\"\n9 mmm\nDANK TELLER John\nMcMahon: \"I'm han\ndling money by the thou\nsands. Jangled nerves\njust don't fit in that kind\nof work. So it's Camels\nfor me.\"\nAUTO MECHANIC A1\nPatterson: \"In the gar\nage business you have to\ncatch your meals on the\nrun. Camels seem to\nsmooth the way for good\ndigestion.\"\nCHIEF SIGNALMAN\nof N. Y. Central R. R.,\nJohn Geraghty: \"Speed\nand safety our watch\nwords call for healthy\nnerves. Do Camels jan\ngle my nerves? No sir!\"\nNEW DOUBLE-FEATURE\nCAMEL CARAVAN\nTwo jsrcal shows\u2014\"Jack Oakic College\" and\nBenny Goodman's \"SwinR School\"\u2014 in one fait,\nfun-filled hour. On ihe air every Tuesday nifchi at\n9:30 pm E.S.T., 8:30 pni C.S.T.. 7:30 pm M.S.T.,\n0:30 piu P.S.T., over WAUC-Columbia Network.\nCvwrwtil. IKI7, U. J. TnlwioCiimitni. **'!\u00bb<to\u00ab-S\u00bbi<\n\\mMK6\u00a3Sr-SEU/m\nI oaaantmMteetn","height":"28266","width":"20892"}}
